{"title_page": "Sallie Alcorn", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Sallie Alcorn\n|image         = \n|office        = [[Houston City Council]] At-Large Position 5\n|term_start    = January 2, 2020\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = Jack Christie\n|successor     = \n|birth_name    = \n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place   = \n|death_date    = \n|death_place   =\n|restingplace = \n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse        = George Alcorn\n|children      = 4\n|residence     = \n|alma_mater     = [[University of Texas at Austin]]<br>[[University of Houston]]\n|occupation    = \n}}\n'''Sallie Alcorn''' is a [[Houston]] politician who represents At-Large Position 5 of the [[Houston City Council]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAlcorn moved to [[Houston]] when she was in the 7th grade. She attended [[University of Texas at Austin]] and graduated with a finance degree. Additionally, she earned, from the [[University of Houston]], a master of arts in public administration. She is married to George Alcorn and they have 4 children. Alcorn is a member of St. Michael the Archangel Catholic Church.<ref name=a/>\n\n==Political career==\nBefore being elected into the Houston City Council she was a staffer for 3 other city councilors. She also served as Chief of Staff to the chair of the budget and fiscal affairs committee, where she helped with the cities budget.<ref name=a>{{cite web |title=About the Council Member |url=https://www.houstontx.gov/council/5/about.html |website=www.houstontx.gov |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2019 election, Alcorn considered to be a more progressive Democrat was challenging more conservative Republican Eric Dick.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eric Dick |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Eric_Dick |website=Ballotpedia |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Alcorn wasn't only backed by the Harris County Young Democrats, but also by the Houston Police Union.<ref>{{cite web |title=Don\u2019t forget to vote for our endorsed candidates in the Saturday Houston city runoff election \u2013 Houston Police Officers\u2019 Union |url=https://hpou.org/dont-forget-to-vote-for-our-endorsed-candidates-in-the-saturday-houston-city-runoff-election/ |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> Throughout her campaign, Alcorn raised $583,000 which made her the most expensive winning candidate for the election cycle.<ref>{{cite web |title=Want A Seat On Houston City Council? That Will Be $11 Per Vote, Please |url=https://www.houstonpublicmedia.org/articles/news/city-of-houston/2020/01/21/357891/want-a-seat-on-houston-city-council-that-will-be-11-per-vote-please/ |website=Houston Public Media |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=21 January 2020}}</ref> The final vote was Alcorn 52.84% of the vote and Dick 47.16% of the vote flipping the seat from Republican to Democratic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Houston City Council Runoff Election Results 2019 |url=https://patch.com/texas/houston/houston-city-council-runoff-election-results-2019 |website=Houston, TX Patch |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=14 December 2019}}</ref>  \n\nAlcorn assumed office to represent At-Large Position 5 of the [[Houston City Council]] on January 2, 2020 succeeding Jack Christie.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sallie Alcorn |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Sallie_Alcorn |website=Ballotpedia |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sallie Alcorn - Texas State Directory Online |url=https://www.txdirectory.com/online/person/?id=65108&office=7180 |website=www.txdirectory.com |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=b/>\n\n===Policies===\nAlcorn is affiliated with the [[Democratic Party (U.S.)|Democratic Party]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sallie Alcorn \u2013 Off the Kuff |url=https://www.offthekuff.com/wp/?tag=sallie-alcorn |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2019 Municipal Elections |url=http://www.harrisyds.org/2019-municipal-elections.html |website=Harris County Young Democrats |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlcorn has supported policies that would allow rideshare companies like [[Uber]] and [[Lyft]] to operate in [[Houston]]. According to her [[NARAL]] questionnaire, she is an advocate for abortion rights and would support government health care programs such as [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] and [[Medicaid]] to cover abortion procedures.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://prochoicetexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Sallie-Alcorn.pdf |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> On infrastructure issues, she wants to provide car-free transportation for Houstonians to ease congestion and improve the cities irrigation to prevent flooding.<ref name=b>{{cite web |last1=Whalen |first1=Emma |title=Houston Runoff Voter Guide 2019: City Council At-Large Position 5 candidates Eric Dick and Sallie Alcorn |url=https://communityimpact.com/houston/heights-river-oaks-montrose/vote/2019/12/03/houston-runoff-voter-guide-2019-city-council-at-large-position-5-candidates-eric-dick-and-sallie-alcorn/ |website=impact |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=English |date=3 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alcorn, Sallie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Texas Democrats]]\n[[Category:Houston City Council members]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Austin alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Sallie Alcorn\n|image         = \n|office        = [[Houston City Council]] At-Large Position 5\n|term_start    = January 2, 2020\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = Jack Christie\n|successor     = \n|birth_name    = \n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place   = \n|death_date    = \n|death_place   =\n|restingplace = \n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse        = George Alcorn\n|children      = 4\n|residence     = \n|alma_mater     = [[University of Texas at Austin]]<br>[[University of Houston]]\n|occupation    = \n}}\n'''Sallie Alcorn''' is a [[Houston]] politician who represents At-Large Position 5 of the [[Houston City Council]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAlcorn moved to [[Houston]] when she was in the 7th grade. She attended [[University of Texas at Austin]] and graduated with a finance degree. Additionally, she earned, from the [[University of Houston]], a master of arts in public administration. She is married to George Alcorn and they have 4 children. Alcorn is a member of St. Michael the Archangel Catholic Church.<ref name=a/>\n\n==Political career==\nBefore being elected into the Houston City Council she was a staffer for 3 other city councilors. She also served as Chief of Staff to the chair of the budget and fiscal affairs committee, where she helped with the cities budget.<ref name=a>{{cite web |title=About the Council Member |url=https://www.houstontx.gov/council/5/about.html |website=www.houstontx.gov |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2019 election, Alcorn considered to be a more progressive Democrat was challenging more conservative Republican Eric Dick.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eric Dick |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Eric_Dick |website=Ballotpedia |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Alcorn wasn't only backed by the Harris County Young Democrats, but also by the Houston Police Union.<ref>{{cite web |title=Don\u2019t forget to vote for our endorsed candidates in the Saturday Houston city runoff election \u2013 Houston Police Officers\u2019 Union |url=https://hpou.org/dont-forget-to-vote-for-our-endorsed-candidates-in-the-saturday-houston-city-runoff-election/ |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> Throughout her campaign, Alcorn raised $583,000 which made her the most expensive winning candidate for the election cycle.<ref>{{cite web |title=Want A Seat On Houston City Council? That Will Be $11 Per Vote, Please |url=https://www.houstonpublicmedia.org/articles/news/city-of-houston/2020/01/21/357891/want-a-seat-on-houston-city-council-that-will-be-11-per-vote-please/ |website=Houston Public Media |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=21 January 2020}}</ref> The final vote was Alcorn 52.84% of the vote and Dick 47.16% of the vote flipping the seat from Republican to Democratic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Houston City Council Runoff Election Results 2019 |url=https://patch.com/texas/houston/houston-city-council-runoff-election-results-2019 |website=Houston, TX Patch |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=14 December 2019}}</ref>  \n\nAlcorn assumed office to represent At-Large Position 5 of the [[Houston City Council]] on January 2, 2020 succeeding Jack Christie.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sallie Alcorn |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Sallie_Alcorn |website=Ballotpedia |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sallie Alcorn - Texas State Directory Online |url=https://www.txdirectory.com/online/person/?id=65108&office=7180 |website=www.txdirectory.com |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=b/>\n\n===Policies===\nAlcorn is affiliated with the [[Democratic Party (U.S.)|Democratic Party]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sallie Alcorn \u2013 Off the Kuff |url=https://www.offthekuff.com/wp/?tag=sallie-alcorn |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2019 Municipal Elections |url=http://www.harrisyds.org/2019-municipal-elections.html |website=Harris County Young Democrats |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlcorn has supported policies that would allow rideshare companies like [[Uber]] and [[Lyft]] to operate in [[Houston]]. According to her [[NARAL]] questionnaire, she is an advocate for abortion rights and would support government health care programs such as [[Medicare]] and [[Medicaid]] to cover abortion procedures.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://prochoicetexas.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Sallie-Alcorn.pdf |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> On infrastructure issues, she wants to provide car-free transportation for Houstonians to ease congestion and improve the cities irrigation to prevent flooding.<ref name=b>{{cite web |last1=Whalen |first1=Emma |title=Houston Runoff Voter Guide 2019: City Council At-Large Position 5 candidates Eric Dick and Sallie Alcorn |url=https://communityimpact.com/houston/heights-river-oaks-montrose/vote/2019/12/03/houston-runoff-voter-guide-2019-city-council-at-large-position-5-candidates-eric-dick-and-sallie-alcorn/ |website=impact |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=English |date=3 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alcorn, Sallie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Texas Democrats]]\n[[Category:Houston City Council members]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Austin alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Medicare\u2192Medicare (United States)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sallie_Alcorn"}
